<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>To:  Environmental Audit Committee                                                 Chase Plastics Ltd</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Chaste Plastics Ltd</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This response pertains solely to the potential exemption of biodegradable bags from the proposed carrier bag tax and the potential damage this will have on the current UK plastic reprocessing sector.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Chase Plastics Ltd has been reprocessing polythene film plastic for 50 years and has seen the rise and fall and rise again of the degradable lobby many times since the 1980s.  Each time our industry has had to point out the pitfalls of promoting degradable bags as the environmental option when it simply is NOT.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Chase Plastics Ltd is a member of the BPFRG and also is a member of the specific Films Working Group from this organisation.  We attended the Defra roundtable workshop where we clearly stated that degradable polymer of any type is NOT recyclable except in total isolation from all other polythene film in the waste stream.  Sadly within days the carrier bag tax had been announced and more alarmingly the suggestion that biodegradable bags should carry an exemption.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Forgive the basic nature of this response but due to a family bereavement I only have today to submit this response.  However I wish simply to add our support to other more in depth submissions.</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Chase Plastics Ltd has no objection to the carrier bag tax.  Although we do not believe it will prevent littering it may lead to more careful use of carrier bags and reduce there abundance.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In other countries including Wales where a tax has been brought in for environmental and littering reasons, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> single use carrier bags have been included in the tax.  A bio degradable bag is absolutely a single use carrier bag and should therefore not carry an exemption. I attach the Welsh Assembly  Single Use Carrier Bag study in which at Paragraph 1.2.8 it sets out the reasons why an exemption is not given. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Government recycling target for Plastic is extremely high.  WRAP has suggested that one of the ways of meeting this ambitious target is to significantly increase the amount of reprocessing of domestic polythene film waste.  Principally, this will be in the form of carrier bags brought back to store.  Further a whole new company has been funded with tax payers money mainly to do just this.  If an exemption is given to biodegradable bags this waste stream will immediately be contaminated and onward reprocessing will not be possible.  The entire domestic film waste stream will have been compromised and none of it, biodegradable and non biodegradable, will be reprocessed here or abroad.  It will have to be landfilled or incinerated.  Effectively the exemption for Biodegradable bags will eliminate the domestic plastic film waste stream from contributing to the targets.  This would seem a very unfortunate outcome.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although Chase Plastics Ltd is not currently involved in reprocessing carrier bags, we do process 1000s of tonnes of polythene film waste.  Should the misguided use of biodegradable bags and other packaging start to be used on any large scale then our own waste stream will be threatened also.  Only very small levels of degradable contamination is needed to totally undermine the integrity of our reprocessed polythene compounds.  Many applications that our material goes into are long lived, damp proof course etc, our customers will quickly abandon our product and return to the safety of using virgin polymer if our material starts to break down once in its given application. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Even Defra’s own research did not find biodegradable bags to be environmentally the best option.  In carbon terms they are significantly more burdensome on the environment than a reprocessed plastic bag.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If the idea is that a biodegradable bag is somehow ‘acceptable’ to litter because it will break down in the environment, then we would strongly reject notion.  We believe that an unintended consequence of this exemption would be more litter not less.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A biodegradable bag is the ultimate problem ‘single use’ carrier.  Although they do not break down totally in order not to prevent a litter problem, the do not last beyond one shop.  Personal experience taught me this when Tescos adopted this kind of bag a few years ago.  A reprocessed plastic c arrier bag however, with its admirable environmental credentials, also can be sturdy and quite fit for repeated uses.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If Government really want to meet their environmental agenda and serve the UK reprocessing sector, which is grossly disadvantaged by other problems with legislation which encourage the export of UK waste packaging, then it should consider an exemption for reprocessed carrier bags.  This would immediately give much needed end markets for UK plastic reprocessors  which would in turn help deliver the UK target, and the even greater European target which may be around the corner.  These bags would be fit for reuse, not ridiculously light weighted so they break before you get your shopping home. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Chase Plastics Ltd would strongly urge this committee to consider a really joined up approach to our environmental problems and outcomes.  You have an opportunity to prevent a well intentioned but misguided error, but you also have the opportunity to offer a huge boost to UK plastic reprocessing by giving the exemption to the best environmental option…..the reprocessed plastic bag.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">6 December 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>